propertyDescriptions.fileName: The data-file file name. This is just the file name and does not included any path information
propertyDescriptions.fileSizeInBytes: The size of the file in bytes
propertyDescriptions.sha256Digest:
A SHA256 digest of the Data File contents. This is a 64 characters long hexadecimal string. 

For example, the SHA256 digest of the string, "RADx Data Hub" is `ebff8d3da88b292622d3bfc36bdac4c4537ddc56cb07f344c5223d6b6f9cd011`.

On macOS the following command may be used to generate the SHA256 digest of a file.

```
shasum -a 256 /path/to/file
```
propertyDescriptions.mediaType: The Media type. For Comma Separated Values files (CSV) the mime type is [text/csv](https://w3id.org/gdmt/tex-csv)
propertyDescriptions.titles:
A title or descriptive name by which the data-file being described is known. This is a presentation name (i.e. title case with appropriate spacing) and is typically different from the actual file name of the data file.

Multiple titles and different languages may be specified.
propertyDescriptions.version:
The string identifying the version of the data-file.

This field accepts any version string, but we suggest that semantic versioning of the form `major.minor.patch`. for example, `2.1.4`, is used.
propertyDescriptions.dataDictionaryFileName: The file name of the Data Dictionary file that defines the Data File's data elements.
propertyDescriptions.isHarmonized: Files containing Tier 1 CDEs that are harmonized across studies and DCCs should be labeled as "Yes." Files that have not been harmonized should be labeled as "No".
propertyDescriptions.origcopyFileName: The name of the original, non-harmonized data file that serves as the source for the harmonized dataset. This file contains data in its pre-harmonized state, making it ready for analysis by Data Hub users. It must follow the naming convention with the suffix "_DATA_origcopy.csv" to distinguish it from harmonized files.
propertyDescriptions.transformcopyFileName: The name of the transformed data file derived from an origcopy file, containing data elements harmonized to Tier 1 CDEs. It must follow the naming convention with the suffix "_DATA_transformcopy.csv" to indicate its harmonized status.
propertyDescriptions.publicationUrls: A list of web links to published research articles, reports, or other relevant sources related to the data file. These URLs serve as references to publications that document, analyze, or utilize the data.
propertyDescriptions.variableNames: A list of variable names that are describe the data contained in this data file
propertyDescriptions.dataDescription: A free text description of the data file contents.
propertyDescriptions.dataDomain: The domain that the data contained in the data file pertains to.
propertyDescriptions.dataCollectionMethod: The data collection methods used to collect the data contained in the data file.
propertyDescriptions.studyCenterType: Whether a single center or multi center study
propertyDescriptions.subjects: The Medical Subject Headings (MeSH) subject code that identifies a classification subject that is pertinent to the data.
propertyDescriptions.keywords: Free text subject, keyword, classification code, or key phrase describing the data file or purpose for which the data file can be used. While MeSH codes are the preferred form of specifying subjects this free text field may be used for codes or subject keywords that do not have a corresponding MeSH terms.
propertyDescriptions.ageGroups: The set of age groups reported in the data.
propertyDescriptions.races: The set of races reported in the data.
propertyDescriptions.ethnicGroups: The set of ethnic groups reported in the data.
propertyDescriptions.sexes: Set set of sexes reported in the data.
propertyDescriptions.educationLevels: The set of education levels reported in the data.
propertyDescriptions.employmentStatuses: The set of employment statuses reported in the data.
propertyDescriptions.insuranceStatuses: The set of insurance statuses reported in the data.
propertyDescriptions.disabilityStatuses: The set of disability statuses reported in the data.
propertyDescriptions.medicalHistories: The set of medical histories reported in the data.  This included things such as history of smoking, history of coronary artery disease etc.
propertyDescriptions.symptoms: The set of symptoms reported in the data.  This includes things such as difficulty breathing, cough, change or loss in apetite etc.
propertyDescriptions.dataCharacteristicsTable: Formatted HTML code for a table of summary statistics.

propertyDescriptions.headerRowColumnNames: Specifies a list of column names that are contained in the header row.  The items in list should be ordered in the same ordering as the columns in the data file.
propertyDescriptions.rowCount: The number of rows in the CSV file (including empty rows).  This includes the header rows.  Thus if there is one header row and ten data rows the row count is 11.
propertyDescriptions.columnCount: The number of columns in the CSV file (including empty columns)

propertyDescriptions.organizationIdentifier: A list of identifiers for the organization
propertyDescriptions.organizationIdentifierScheme:
**Identifier Scheme:**
- **Purpose:** This field specifies how to interpret an identifier when it is provided as a plain string.
- **Value:** The value of this field must be a controlled term.
- **Special Cases:**
  - If the identifier is an Internationalized Resource Identifier (IRI), a Uniform Resource Identifier (URI), or a URL, this field should be left blank.
- **Recommendation:**
  - We strongly recommend using URIs or IRIs whenever possible to ensure clarity and consistency in identifier interpretation.
- **Example:**
  - If the value for an ORCID is provided as `https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1825-0097`, it is clear that this is a URI, and the identifier scheme field can be left blank.
  - However, if the identifier is given as `0000-0002-1825-0097`, the identifier scheme must specify that this is an ORCID, so it can be correctly interpreted.

organizationIdentifierScheme.schema:name: organizationIdentifierScheme
organizationIdentifierScheme.schema:description:
**Identifier Scheme:**
- **Purpose:** This field specifies how to interpret an identifier when it is provided as a plain string.
- **Value:** The value of this field must be a controlled term.
- **Special Cases:**
  - If the identifier is an Internationalized Resource Identifier (IRI), a Uniform Resource Identifier (URI), or a URL, this field should be left blank.
- **Recommendation:**
  - We strongly recommend using URIs or IRIs whenever possible to ensure clarity and consistency in identifier interpretation.
- **Example:**
  - If the value for an ORCID is provided as `https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1825-0097`, it is clear that this is a URI, and the identifier scheme field can be left blank.
  - However, if the identifier is given as `0000-0002-1825-0097`, the identifier scheme must specify that this is an ORCID, so it can be correctly interpreted.

propertyDescriptions.contributorIdentifier:
Globally unique string that identifies the contributor (an individual or legal entity). For individuals, this is typically an ORCID; for research organizations, it is typically an ROR.

The ORCID iD is an https IRI with a 16-digit number that is compatible with the ISO Standard (ISO 27729), also known as the International Standard Name Identifier (ISNI), e.g. https://orcid.org/0000-0001-2345-6789 

_[ORCID](https://orcid.org) provides a persistent digital identifier (an ORCID iD) that distinguishes each researcher from every other researcher. You can connect your iD with your professional information—affiliations, grants, publications, peer review, and more. You can use your iD to share your information with other systems, ensuring you get recognition for all your contributions, saving you time and hassle, and reducing the risk of errors._

The ROR is an https IRI that uniquely identifies most research organizatiions. 

_The [Research Organization Registry (ROR)](https://ror.org) is a community-led project to develop an open, sustainable, usable, and unique identifier for every research organization in the world._

- **Example:**

  - However, if the identifier is given as `0000-0002-1825-0097`, the identifier scheme must specify that this is an ORCID, so it can be correctly interpreted.

propertyDescriptions.contributorAffiliationName: If the contributor is a person, the organizational or institutional affiliation of the contributor.
propertyDescriptions.contributorAffiliationIdentifier:
Globally unique string that identifies the organizational affiliation of the contributor.  

We suggest that you an identifier from the [Research Organization Registry (ROR)](https://ror.org), a community-led project to develop an open, sustainable, usable, and unique identifier for every research organization in the world.

If you would like to provide a US Government Unique Entity Identifier (UEI) then you should provide it here. A Unique Entity Identifier is a 12-character alphanumeric ID assigned to an entity by SAM.gov.  UEIs replace DUNS numbers.  For example, the unique entity identifier for Stanford University is `HJD6G4D6TJY5`.

items.title: dates element schema
items.description: dates element is generated by CEDAR CLI

propertyDescriptions.eventType: Type of Data File event that the date is associated with. The Event Type is usually considered with respect to the corresponding actor; for example, Created is typically the initial creation of the Data File by its originator, Accepted is when an ingested Data File is approved (e.g., by the Data Hub), and Updated is the time of the most recent change to the Data File.
propertyDescriptions.date:
The date/time that is specific to the associated event. 

Note that dates must be specified in [ISO-8601](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601) format. This format specifies date/times in a locale neutral way with temporal components ordered largest to smallest, for example year, month, day. Note that times are in 24 hour clock (military time) format, thus 13:43 is 1:43pm. When times are specified a time zone must also be specified (Z or +00:00 indicates Greenwich Mean Time).

The date time 2022-11-23T01:23:45.678-07:00 specifies November 23, 2022 at just past 1:23am Pacific Daylight Time. Hyphens and colons are optional.

The date 2022-09-23 specifies September 23, 2022 (without a time stamp). Dates are assumed GMT if no time zone is specified.

items.schema:name: dates
items.schema:description:
A list of relevant dates related to the data file being described. Such dates pertain to some data-file-related event, for example "creation date", "submission date" etc. Dates are specified as a pair containing the actual date (in ISO-8601 format) and the event that the date relates to. See individual fields for specific examples.

The dates of some types of events can be captured by the RADx Data Hub, for example the "Submitted" date/time.

funderIdentifierScheme.title: funderIdentifierScheme field schema
funderIdentifierScheme.description: funderIdentifier is generated by CEDAR CLI
funderIdentifierScheme.schema:name: funderIdentifierScheme
funderIdentifierScheme.schema:description:
**Identifier Scheme:**
- **Purpose:** This field specifies how to interpret an identifier when it is provided as a plain string.
- **Value:** The value of this field must be a controlled term.
- **Special Cases:**
  - If the identifier is an Internationalized Resource Identifier (IRI), a Uniform Resource Identifier (URI), or a URL, this field should be left blank.
- **Recommendation:**
  - We strongly recommend using URIs or IRIs whenever possible to ensure clarity and consistency in identifier interpretation.
- **Example:**
  - If the value for an ORCID is provided as `https://orcid.org/0000-0002-1825-0097`, it is clear that this is a URI, and the identifier scheme field can be left blank.
  - However, if the identifier is given as `0000-0002-1825-0097`, the identifier scheme must specify that this is an ORCID, so it can be correctly interpreted.
